title: Sup Mate
write_up: Future/Young Thug, as the defacto Modest Mouse/Built to Spill of the Atlanta generation of rap music, have made a lot of music together, even an entire project. Sup Mate is my personal favorite, as it shows what happens when geniuses are given the space to interplay artistically with each other. They must have been off their ass when they made it, so much of it feels almost ridiculously instinctual, which of course anyone who knows their musical style can tell isn’t an act. There are so many great throw away lines here, sticky like fish guts, that make ‘Sup Mate’ an alive work of art which can make a sleepless bus drive from Sevilla to Valencia in the middle of the night somehow worthwhile. The secret is having someone to think about.
lyric: I should teach drug classes

title: Look At Me!
write_up: It’s hard to shock teenagers. For a month or two, XXX did, and it made him famous. He did it for countless more kids over the course of the next couple of years before he died. The crude sexuality doubles both as a gateway to his perverse and sociopathic intrusive thoughts, and as a loud and clear warning for why you should stay the fuck away from him.
lyric: I put a hole in your parents, aye

title: Please
write_up: Indie Rock burns with a quiet sort of passion that passerby seem to sense is really just passivity. I hate that. It’s passive not to care, it’s passive to choose money over soul, it’s passive to believe in yourself and not in the world, it’s passive to choose the easy way out every single time. ‘Please’ is a literal plea for others to understand, a mazy trek of a song which has emotional peaks and valleys, like real life, but as it is only a work of art and not an actual life with real human experience, people ignore it if it just doesn’t benefit their life enough to care.

title: Imaginary Person
write_up: Garage rock is fun, that’s the whole point of it. ‘Imaginary Person’ takes that fun and adds a psychological edge to it, ruining the fun for some people, but for others, taking what would be only a few minutes of fun and turning it into a whole day of it. I just mean, from playing the song over and over again. Because you, you are, an imaginary person. You’re in my head. I’m certain, you are real. Yeah!

title: Scope (feat. Sickboyrari)
write_up: WifiGawd isn’t a particularly important rapper from the last decade, but like featured artist Sickboyrari (AKA Black Kray), he is one of those subtly great rappers who work very hard and eventually hit gold every now and then. Scope is a song I know because of my friend Robbie, which makes sense, it’s the sort of song that gets passed around like a blunt, every person getting their little piece of pleasure from it. DC music. Woo.
lyric: Right on Georgia Ave

title: I Am Who They Say I Am
write_up: There are some people who are born with an instinctive gift for singing their heart out in a non-embarrassing way. It’s otherwise known as artistic talent. NBA YoungBoy is one of them, and though his personal life shows that world he grew up in is far from a thing of the past, there’s a plain beauty to reinterpreting the harshness of the world into pop music. He believes in himself as an artist, in his unique individuality particularly, and while it isn’t always convincing, it makes for great music when it comes together.
lyric: Look for my mama when I try to look inside my woman

title: So Sick With It
write_up: Helvetia has been a quiet well for quality indie rock for some time now, and part of it is in the distinctiveness of the music. He has a particular brand of hushed sad boy vocals that just fits well with the mess of wheeling guitars. I will always admire men who sing openly about jealousy, as it’s one of those things that the wrong sort of woman will take for weakness, and it’s scary to find out whether or not someone sometimes is that sort.
lyric: I always pushed you away when you tried to open up / Can’t stand to see you with him, even just in a dream

title: No Hands (feat. Roscoe Dash & Wale)
write_up: For anyone who hasn’t grown up in the American public school system, here’s your chance to head to a school dance. Sing the words, jump up and down a bit, stand with your arms around shoulders in a circle with everyone else while the drunk and self-absorbed kids dance in the middle of it, you got it, don’t worry, because later on, you’ll be in bed and you’ll feel that really wasn’t too bad.

title: Caramel Emotion
write_up: Someone hurt this girl. I mean like, Jesus Christ, emotion has never come so easily to any band this century. Ava Trilling, as well as Ben Guterl, were little geniuses overflowing with talent. From what I can understand, ‘Caramel Emotion’ is written about a close teen friendship turning unhappily into romantic love. However, what makes Forth Wanderers different, is that when I played this on my radio show the old man who ran a 70s station the hour before me called me up, begging to know the name of the band and the name of this song. Some people can just create things that go beyond the limits of their adolescent experience.
lyric: I kept all your secrets safe / nothing in return, ‘cept your imprint on my brain

title: Voodoo
write_up: ‘Voodoo’ has a lot of faults, probably more faults than any other song on this list. It’s still a special song, because Keef is literally the only person on earth who can make unique creepy-clown production into dark trap epics. Not only is he the only person strange enough to have this kind of vision, but he is also the only person with the wherewithal to make it happen, to have the ability to turn subtly vivid subconscious ideas into works of art.

title: Ur My Bby
write_up: Aesthetics are nice, they give you a chance to attach a personal enjoyment to something from only a second or two of consumption. Pop music is not just about aesthetics though, it’s about precise songwriting, hard work, and innovation. So aesthetics, essentially, are that all-important initial bridge between our ingrained sense of utility and the real artistic meat of the work. From the first fifteen seconds of ‘Ur My Bby, we understand the aesthetic appeal of its old school and lo-fi melody, but it’s over the course of the rest of the song when we see all the pieces really come together, even without any words.

title: Your Brain is Made of Candy
write_up: Some songs are just what they are, you know, like the title just explains it, and then within twenty seconds or so, the rest of the song is clear too. ‘Your Brain is Made of Candy’ is one of those songs, it’s just one of those audience pleasers that doesn’t quite make sense but which has a palpating tension and an inherent outright catchiness. There’s an emotional specificity to the title line too that keeps it in your mind long after you hear it.
lyric: Oh your brain’s made of candy / At first I thought it was rancid

title: The Club
write_up: Hinds are from Spain, and in an interview I saw them talk about the Strokes like it was the Rolling Stones talking about Muddy Waters. It’s not hard to see that sort of appeal to their music, which is about making Indie Rock like they’re all stuck at the bottom of those Korean factories that spit out heavily marketable boy bands like it’s what they eat for breakfast. Unique to them are the overlapping melodies of their two vocalists and the nice and friendly way their bandmates can stay in step with them.

title: La Flare Freestyle
write_up: There’s really something to a group of friends on a cut together, having fun, exploring that fun feeling of masculine overconfidence, never taking anything too seriously. La Flare Freestyle takes that idea and explodes into real, living music. Each of them, while Sensei ATL is more the production mastermind, bring their own specific flavor of bravado to it, making the song even that more replayable.
lyric: Randy Timberlake, I’ll take your bitch like N-Sync

title: After You
write_up: After You is the only leak on this list. I wouldn’t have included it, first-draft mumbled verses and all, if I didn’t still think it was a finished artistic product in a way. He can reinterpret this again if he wants but I don’t even know if it would still have the same sort of emotional power he gets across here just from freestyling. Sometimes, when the production is perfect, you can catch something real from somewhere inside you as you invent on the spot. Just being alone with yourself and your voice and your thoughts is enough.
lyric: You know the evil that men do

title: Happy to See Me
write_up: Hop Along have released three great albums this decade, but my personal favorite is painted shut, which glows from song to song, hook to hook, until the songs are indistinguishable from each other yet still clearly separate when you actually listen to one of them. The backing band is not especially important here, instead it’s the up-and-down, quiet-and-loud, constant contradictions of Quinlan’s unique Midwestern Emo singing style that make it so good.
lyric: Father gets up at 4 A.M. / To post a motivational video on youtube again

title: Pilot Light
write_up: Sour Widows reminds me of a classic indie rock outfit, not one that comes to mind necessarily, but really just some band with that sort of naturalistic ethos that powers invaluable music. Their defining trait is the wandering emotion of the lead singer Susanna Thomson and the subsequent slow-build quality of their songs gradually becoming more important and revelatory. Similar to their more recent songs like ‘Whole Lotta Nothing’ and ‘Crossing Over’, ‘Pilot Light’ attacks human sensation with a riotous desire to understand. The song’s subject matter is actually strikingly similar to ‘Breakthrough’ off of ‘This Is a Long Drive for Someone With Nothing to Think About’. Maybe it’s that band I first had in mind.

title: I Swear
write_up: There’s going to be a lot of Atlanta rappers on this list. Johnny Cinco might be the most consistent of all of them. It’s been years and he’s still making the same type of hits. Furred shelters of songs that pound hard and believe in themselves. He has one of the strongest senses for stage presence of any rapper out there.

title: Been Had Sauce
write_up: Young Thug and Future by this point in 2022 have more or less abandoned their artistic uniqueness in the attempt to secure hits like Lil Baby and Lil Durk have been able to do. While some have seen this is as an example of their waning influence as artists, the existence of underground rappers like BoofPaxkMooky show it to be more just a sign of the times. The same indelible taste for sonically exploratory trap music lives on, only this time, it’s people who know they have to do something new. BoofPaxk’s hiccupy style takes some getting used to, but eventually his charm and spatial talent win you over, just like those old guys used too.
lyric: Swag major, major, Been had sauce / Been had sauce, swag, major

title: Carnival Dough
write_up: Indie Pop, especially weird sounding Indie Pop, especially weird sounding Indie Pop from Baltimore, will always be compared to Animal Collective. Sun Club do it a little different though, using the stylistic basicness of the genre to invent their own little fun, less abrasive than the collective, but still doing things for all the right reasons, soaring into the self-created heights like there’s no tomorrow.

title: Don't Know What To Do
write_up: Arbes make vibey music for the sake of making vibey music. True, a lot of other bands do that. I can name a few that made it big off of Spotify in the last couple years. Their artistic sensibility is stronger than those acts though, even if they don’t have the numbers to show for it. The vibes here exist in the sophisticated distance, able to be enjoyed but never to feel in excess. The beach guitars are a nice change too for this style of music.
lyric: Don’t waste your time

title: Hurt Real Bad
write_up: A legend of Atlanta music, Trouble was luckily given an entire album with Mike WiLL Made-It to show his brilliance before he passed. Its best songs, like Hurt Real Bad, are about how pain sinks into our skin until we can no longer feel it anymore. These songs, tacitly exploring the long standing blues tradition of the American South, are subtly spiritualistic pieces of a mind gradually losing itself in the streets.

title: Junk of the Heart (Happy)
write_up: This song is the only song on this list that has been placed for sentimental purposes. All the rest I honestly believe to be the best songs of the decade. Not that I would argue with anyone who said ‘Junk of the Heart’ was that great, it’s just that it’s only on this list because no other song has been as singularly important for my passion for music. I was in 5th grade when Julia Arnsberger caught me looking at her, and as she quickly looked away and annoyedly rolled her eyes, I heard perfectly that tune of ‘I want to make you happy’ repeating somewhere deep inside me. A year or two later, standing in my room, looking out the window over a foreign city, I listened to it again so I could be transported back, skin and soul and all, to my hometown. I made sure to only listen to it once and a while, so the feeling would last. It was like time travel. And yeah I guess, it’s also just a great song.

title: They Want My Soul
write_up: All across this album is the evidence of a band working for nobody but themselves. It leads, in many different directions, into pop music success, but never so brutally as in ‘They Want My Soul’, which uses standard chord changes and rock n’ roll energy normally but without all of the pride other songs like it, on this album and elsewhere, have. Spoon will be remembered as one of the most consistent indie acts of the early 21st century, which is not a small accomplishment by any means.

title: The Violence Inside
write_up: Guitar pop and indie music in general fans, you can eat your heart out with An Ettendant Ana. In terms of influences, it wouldn’t make much sense to get into it, but Alvvays fans will most likely love it. The French have been important to popular music like no other non-English speaking country, showing that qualified artistic sensibilities can arise from anywhere on earth. To borrow from that popular American movie which was clearly in love with French culture: ‘Not everyone can be a great cook, but, anyone can be a great cook’.

title: Avian
write_up: Mac Miller, through albums like Blue Side Park, Divine Feminine, and Swimming, proved himself to be a gifted rapper. He never wows at first hearing, but he is always able to fit seamlessly into the beat. On his best songs, he finds pockets of wisdom from the back of his mind, like in Avian, where he quips “TV Money / Dollar for sense of humor” and “Not into this conversation, I been in my head for hours, I’m out.” These lyrics perfectly encapstulate the (drug-related) feeling of wanting to escape our bodies:
lyric: There's a bird in the sky / Look at him fly / Why, why, why, why, why

title: Blonde Blood
write_up: Boyscott’s debut album is filled with warm, catchy surf-guitar licks. The songs carefully bend through subtle emotional dynamics, which the whispery soft vocals clearly echo, but what’s most impressive is how trivial, fun and easy they make it sound.
lyric: I might act like I’m an asshole / Mean guys always get close to you

title: Skyfall (ft. Young Thug)
write_up: Travis Scott has built himself a formidable popular legacy over the course of the decade. He has never been an artistic innovator, borrowing from other artists and producers for the basis of his sound, but still, he created a distinctive style. His lyrics have never been strong, but his syrupy robotic vocals here soar through the bridges and at the end of the day, he comes close to Young Thug’s world, which is a credit to him, considering it’s his song.
lyric: I’m it like a game that get played by a kid

title: The Knowing
write_up: Starting with a soft, melancholy Cocteau Twins sample, The Weeknd builds a sonic world through the expansiveness of his vocals. He isn’t as dynamic (or unintelligible) as Elizabeth Fraser, but he understands how to construct cascades of emotion, which swirl beneath him as he proudly rejects an ex-lover.
lyric: You probably thought that you’d break my heart.

title: On God
write_up: After the mainstream explosion in 2016, Soundcloud Rap went into hiding, slowly building itself back up again through Pluggnb, until rappers like Vonte, BoofPaxkMooky, 1600J, Tony Shhnow and 10KDunkin fully arrived, artistic hearts intact. Vonte’s innate stylistic reliance on heavy autotune takes some getting used to, but on songs like ‘On God’, he finds the hidden emotional pathos absent from much of mainstream rap, powered all the time by a brilliant, spectral beat.

title: Home
write_up: LCD Soundsystem isn’t known for pop-gold through brevity, they find it instead through elongated philosophical meanderings, surrounded by straight-forward dance-influenced bass and drum lines, as well as small guitar licks. Home isn’t ‘All My Friends’, or ‘Someone Great’, but it finds a soft transcendence through reimagining the basics that made up those two gargantuan songs. Every component fits perfectly.
lyric: And you stay home, and you better, ‘cause you’re afraid of what you are

title: Broke Boi
write_up: MexikoDro is one of the most influential producers of the decade, and his sensibility is all over Broke Boi, which glides through glittery keys in the light of Carti’s incessant, reckless confidence. Carti’s flow here steals the show, his intonations making the most basic flexes memorable and irresistibly catchy.
lyric: Audi, Beamer, Benz with the roof up

title: Tonya Harding (In D Major)
write_up: Released around the same time as the movie, Sufjan Stevens uses his distinctive prosaic style with the simplicity and eloquence that his name became synonymous with in the wake of his fantastic past released like ‘Michigan’ and ‘Illinois’. Here, like he did in the past with John Wayne Gacy, he calmly talks face-to-face with a larger-than-life American cultural figure, implicitly challenging their standard negative moral connotation.
lyric: She took quite a beating, so you’re not above cheating

title: Say To You
write_up: STRFKR are one of the happiest, most bountifully creative groups of the decade. They’re not particularly substantive, but they have a knack for melodies, which come through the emotionally searing vocals and electronic peripheries of ‘Say to You’. Emotions ae hard to come by in our current day and age. STRFKR lets you arrive to them without any overly-sentimental baggage.

title: Harps
write_up: While their most important music is in their first three projects, the Sea and Cake are one of the most consistently creative indie bands for a reason. Harps starts off at a snail’s pace, but it provides the room for one stunningly clean guitar crescendo. Like their 1997 slow-build epic, ‘The Argument’, the Sea and Cake defy the familiar trappings of indie pop by hiding their gold from sight at first glance.

title: Neighborhood Hero
write_up: Bleakness is standard for drill, but Lil Durk finds his own melodic corner of it. Great lines.

title: Nike Just Do It
write_up: (Come be an absent person with me, this is my world, and it's amazing)

title: Self Control
write_up: Featuring a Yung Lean bridge, Self Control is where Blonde finds itself approaching pop stardom, Frank Ocean bending his voice in and out of a wavering guitar, exploring the edges of how we come to understand ourselves, while never abandoing its mass appeal

title: Lil Haiti Baby
write_up: Shoot in broad day, shoot in broad day

title: Smoke Again (ft. Ab-Soul)
write_up: Before he lost his abilility to control how people thought of him, Chance the Rapper had his reputation for a reason. His music is  silliy and earnest, but it has a unmistakable real youthful driving energy

title: Set Dat Bitch Off (Remix)
write_up: This DC-based, A$AP Mob affialiate never really found his place in the popular rap conversation, though with ICYTWAT's help, here he finds himself navigating being the center of an never ending underground rave as if he'd been there his whole life

title: All Day
write_up: (life is great and I'm happy to be alive)

title: Drunk Drivers / Killer Whales
write_up: Brute force leaves us with nothing to do but react. Cocaine, cocaine, cocaine, with energy and enthusiasim. They didn't particualrly evolve into saying anything different, but they were often able to recreate this initial burst of energy, not only on a local Atlanta scale but on a national and eventually international scale.

title: Erosion
write_up: Greys are not very well known among indie fans, at least not like some mainstream success stories, but it’s not for a lack of hooks. Usually more suited to an aesthetic of hard punk rock, ‘erosion’ shows a sweet melodical instinct that’s closer to the alternative rock trends of the millennium, reminiscent (in a good way) of ‘… And you will know us by the trail of the dead’, but also, fierce and artistically original. Canada.

title: Florida
write_up: Accesible indie-pop that traces over moods quite easily and without every staying too long within its own sentimality. Able to construct something of a world through old-style M83 synths.

title: Brand New
write_up: The second half of the 2010s found rappers entering waves of internet cloud rap clout that vanished as soon as they lost their edge (loosely defined as the marriage between esoteric beat selection and novel melodic sensibility For a year or two, Yung Bans had it in spades.

title: Lance Jr.
write_up: Courtney writes this song for someone who she doesn’t like very much, who she might even hate, but okay, she likes them enough, she admits, to jack off to their songs in order to fall asleep. For one, it’s an unexpected and personal revelation, but it’s also delivered in her off-hand nonchalant way, which makes it catchy, extremely memorable, and somehow a damn good diss song.

title: Ashley Olsen
write_up: Their lyrical back and forth culminates with the great reprise on the choruses

title: Yah Mean
write_up: Almost as if Playboi Carti was never meant to do anything but build emotional soundscapes meant for people who like to feel when they listen to music. The lyrics here, are nothing compared to his ability to layer his vocal intonations over top of each other in the blank spaces of dreamy cloud rap

title: Peach Boy
write_up: Jay Som is another piece of evidence for queer women's indie rock takeover.

title: Devon
write_up: Grimes is the cosmic stadium constructer of the decade, and Devon explores an inner world so unique and personal that it's impossible to emotionally articulate. I want someone to make a song about me like this.

title: I'll Tell You What
write_up: Out of all of Young Thug's most quotable songs, this is at the top. Non-sequitors that really aren't non-sequitors as much as catcchiness inseperapably piled up on top of itself, strange and understated production, trap music at its most unavoidable

title: Uncast Shadow of a Southern Myth
write_up: While their most important music is in their first three projects, the Sea and Cake are one of the most consistently creative indie bands for a reason. Harps glides across the sky.

title: It's Real
write_up: While a step below their more creative self-titled release, it's refined processed slow-paced indie rock that has its heart in the right place.

title: Tity and Dolla (ft. Hugh Augustine and Jay Rock)
write_up: "Mom's said I lost the plot at least I never lost my crop"

title: Headlines
write_up: His popular music omnipresence is hard to take, but his natural stage presence still comes through like a truck. Classic hook.

title: I Like That You Can See It
Hallucinating
write_up: Classic future song, nothing revolutionary in terms of his catalogue, but for any other rapper it would be their greatest song

title: My Flaws Burn Through My Skin Like Demonic Flames From Hell
SMUCKERS (ft. Kanye West and Lil Wayne)
lyric: Tyler, the creator might be the most widely recognizable rapper of the decade. Most kids know who he is, even if they don’t listen to music. He’s always been a prodigious producer, but SMUCKERS shows another side, the ‘Kanye’ pop song touch, building a unique scene, inviting great rappers into it (like Kanye), while he follows his own one a kind artistic instincts.

title: I Bet On Losing Dogs
write_up: (I can't stop ruining my life). Self-destruction is most likely the easiest topic for depressive, lonely, music listeners to connect with.

title: Buss It
write_up: "She say she love me"

title: No
write_up: The lines here, though in Spanish, are wonderfully poetic. No hay que ver el futuro / Para saber lo que va a pasar. (You don't have to see the future to know what's going to happen).

title: Dad
write_up: Takes the emotional ethos of cloud rap and purifies it into a unique vision, accompanied by wonderful production that understands itself perfectly

title: Souljahwitch's Faith
write_up: Lil Tracy filtered his weed addiction/depression into pure agnst, also showing his rare lyrical side

title: Baby What's Wrong With You
write_up: A great song that might be his most outwardly influential. Pretty much establishes: This is what you can do with cloud rap. Have fun.

title: 1539 N. Calvert
write_up: Classic line after classice line. Long extended intro before launching into the most ridicously catchy flow you've ever heard

title: Yeah Yeah
write_up: Longest Hook ever.

title: Super Rich Kids (ft. Earl Sweatshirt)
write_up: While Frank Ocean traces over the many problems that affluent kids can have, Earl Sweartshirt applies his own childhood to a show-stopping verse

title: 2 Cups Stuffed
write_up: (Lean, lean, lean lean lean), (500 DNA in my ding-ding), (L-E-A-N-I-N-G), relentess energy

title: Transitional Bird (Clever Girl)
write_up: Builds sonic worlds, but antithetically to how it’s normally done, stacking incongruences on top of each other, to reach an ultimate sonic whirlwind that is impossible to fully nail down. The vocals aren’t inaudible, it’s just that the song structure is impossible to fully wrap your head around because there’s so much stuff going on at once. You have to keep playing it over and over again to figure it out.

title: Feelin' the Love
write_up: I hear the synths from this song when I wake up in the morning, after not listening to this song for a year or two. Instantly memorable.

title: Rugged Country
write_up: Michele Zauner built Japanese Breakfast single-handedly throughout the decade into a well-regarded mainstream indie pop act.  Many songs could have been on this list, but ‘Rugged Country’ is one of her most isolatorily brilliant pop songs. Seemingly about dating a friend’s ex despite its morbid imagery, her pain and emotional clarity pass perfectly through her vocals, with her guitars behind her, one step at a time.

title: Gentleman
write_up: Mom's said I lost the plot / At least I never lost my crop

title: Bleach
write_up: Cloud Rap has arrived

title: Identikit
write_up: Everyone’s heard a Radiohead song. Some part of their aura will always seem to above all other earthly indie bands, but the 2010s saw the first decade of indie music where Radiohead was not a major player. ‘Identikit’, and ‘A Moon Shaped Pool’ in general, suggest though that the core songwriters could continue to make great music for the foreseeable future (The Smile). ‘Identikit’s guitars meander through shifting backgrounds of soft choruses that rise and fall to produce a surprisingly ear-wormy final product.

title: I JU$T WANN4 BE YO6R FRIEND
Obvs
write_up: Electronic music gets a bad rap. Not from anyone in specific really, but I think as humans we tend to ask less of electronic music than with other genres. Obvs takes us through the emotional soaring highs and ephemeral sensations that all great pop music is supposed to. And unlike other tracks, it’s concise and perfectly manicured. And unlike other tracks, it’s concise and perfectly manicured.

title: Skrt
write_up: When I say I keep the poker, I ain't talking bout no beans

title: A Token of Gratitude
write_up: One of the most important dream-pop bands ever

title: Raw (Might Just)
write_up: No rapper has come close to this world, not even future,

title: He Would Have Laughed
write_up: Sitting at the back of a city bus in Chile

title: Queen Black Acid
write_up: From a seemingly hapharzadly song construction process, Menomena find unsual emotional clarity rather easily

title: Size of the Moon
write_up: (My dad would help because he's smart)

title: Pussy Weed Beer
write_up: Chastity Belt, maybe clearly from the name, was one of the most creatively unique bands of the decade. Unafraid to give albums and songs impulsive and immature names like ‘No Regrets’, ‘Nip Slip’, and of course, ‘Pussy Weed Beer’, the all-female band by nature undercut any preconceived notions someone could bring to their music.
lyric: (I need everything good in my life, and I need it now)

title: Lost
write_up: Danny Brown has the voice of an angel. Maybe not the most sober angel, but an angel nonetheless. His off-the-wall delivery style hides a meticulous writer’s instinct, checking syllables and meanings within a hyena-like voice that makes no sense really (could he even put into words what he’s going for?), but it works, and there’s no one else like him.

title: NuYork Nights at 21
write_up: A song that Pitchfork in another era would have no drawbacks upon labeling a 'stunner'.

title: Depreston
write_up: Courtney Barnett has a genius conversational style, here it slows down into world building. It casually takes the engaged listener around a house, and she complains about the world in ways that bother you too. Courtney Barnett understands her voice a lot more than a lot of more naturally dynamic singers do.

title: Purple Reign
write_up: (Why can't I be happy)

title: M.A.A.D City
write_up: YAK YAK YAK. Kendrick Lamar is rightfully acknoweldged as rap's greatest lyricist of the decade, but here he is somehow able to find pop stardom in the form of a violent relentlessness basking in the urban sprawl of Los Angeles

title: Kill For Love
write_up: Not many pop songs avoid melodrama. ‘Kill for Love’ doesn’t even try. It approaches its heartfelt topics like it’s a first-time experience for everyone involved, including the listeners. One of the most gleeful electronic guitar hooks you’ll ever hear, tied up with a proud vocal performance which reimagines its Beach House influences into something even more purely melancholy.

title: White Tee
write_up: Lil Tracy and Lil Peep were the greatest rap duo of the decade, besides, I guess, Young Thug and Rich Homie Quan, but even then their interplay has nothing on Lil Tracy/Lil Peep who exchange between themselves so effortlessly it's as if they were the same person

title: Woah Woah Woah (ft. Bali Baby)
write_up: Somewhere along the way, Trippie Redd became confused, and it's too bad he did, because if he didn't, we would have had albums full of emotional highs that enter your headspace so conclusively it's hard to imagine of anything except his world

title: Rawlings
write_up: Keef's most pure example of his savant-like sensibility for intros, Rawlings finds his wonderful chemistry with DP Beats reaching into the depths of your heart to pull out what's left of it, its synths excavators, his gritty voice the moon shining its light on you from up above the hole.

title: Devil in a New Dress (ft. Rick Ross)
SomebodyPlease/Armour/Hunger
write_up: SomebodyPlease/Amour/Hunger combines the gritty NY production of its album with some of MIKE's most emotionally direct ramblings in one of the best album openers of the decade. Hard to find an album that fits into its environment better than this one.

title: No Shoes On The Rug, Leave Them At The Door

title: Emergency Blimp
write_up: The Ooz is one of the most cohesive albums of the decade, most of the songs drifting in between dreams and the underworld of a dark city. Emergency Blimp is its wake-up call, bringing in fast-paced guitars, brilliant vocal melodies straight out of ‘Easy Easy’, as well as a drug-related lyrical run-on simmering with artificial creakiness.

title: Sinister
write_up: Frankie Cosmos has a voice that cracks continually, but her perfect intonation style makes us fall for her all the same. The guitars are never wowing, but they allow Frankie Cosmos’s multi-tracked diarisms sink into the heads of the listeners. Her lyrical content is unique and deep, as she ponders friendships and existence and heartbreak and fate within the box of an indie-pop group.

title: Mythological Beauty
write_up: Lauded generally online as the 'start' of what melodic rap could do, Citgo is still as powerful as it likely was (I was listening to the arctic monkeys back then instead) the day it came out. Citgo is one of the premier landmarks for cloud rap.  Chief Keef is a visionary artist who deserves to be listed in the same breath of the Built to Spill, Kurosawa, and Gabriel Garcia Marquez

title: Ribs
write_up: While it is now rightfully recognized as one of her greatest songs, Ribs took some time to reach its current level of fame. I find it hard to believe ‘Ribs’ could ever not be someone’s favorite song off ‘Pure Heroine’. It’s slow-building, confidently arranged, and packed with an insane amount of savant-like emotional insight and innocent youthful purity.

title: Grab The Wheel
write_up: "When I'm in DC they call me Moe". Before I got into Young Thug, Uzi was both the warmth of my hometown and the love of human  feeling. Uzi will always have an almost unberable talent for unique song construction, with melodies effortlessly cascading over each other, and here it comes about as close as you can to perfection. The synths near the end are brilliant.
